<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-085-192  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 085 192.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Office  Jan 1990 v111 n1 p62(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Software developers are striving to meet demands.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dayton, Doug.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Developers of office-automation software strive to meet three keyuser needs: control over personal computing resources, sharing ofdata in work groups, and improving the overall performance ofdistributed systems.andP;  Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) werehighlighted at the 1989 Comdex/Fall trade show; virtually everymajor software developer displayed GUI-based products.andP;  Workgroupautomation systems, many of which will be based on the OS/2platform, will provide voice and data communications and video anddata retrieval across enterprise-wide networks.andP;  Important newnetwork technologies are standards such as the X.400 and X.500protocols, software designed to help managers troubleshootnetworks, and client/server computing, which lets mission-criticaloffice applications run more efficiently.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Office AutomationSoftware DesignSoftware PublishersUser NeedsData CommunicationsGraphical User InterfaceWork Group Computing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>